description:
19 games tested on AMD Ryzen 7 9800X3D PC! Unboxing new NVIDIA GeForce RTX 5090 (Palit GameRock variant) graphics card. DLSS 4, Multi Frame Generation, Reflex 2 and 32GB of GDDR7 memory. Thanks to PALIT for sending the review unit for testing purposes.
All unboxing videos https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLo2sxVnbrTqCxdu55pSRUEQhplewUYE7T

Click to Subscribe!  http://tinyurl.com/klfpd64
Become a member https://www.youtube.com/c/TheRelaxingEnd/join

Second Channel http://www.youtube.com/VeryRelaxing
Twitter https://twitter.com/TheRelaxingEnd
Instagram https://www.instagram.com/relaxingends
Livestream https://www.twitch.tv/therelaxingend
Facebook https://www.facebook.com/TheRelaxingEnd

Please note: at the time of making this video six games had DLSS 4 working (50 series pre-launch):
- Cyberpunk 2077
- Hogwarts Legacy
- Star Wars Outlaws
- Alan Wake 2
- Dragon Age Veilguard (I will maybe buy it when it's on sale for $10)
- Marvel Rivals

comments.text:
It's so weird that they're marketing MFG exclusive for the 50 series when in reality...
It's the previous gen GPUs that would benefit from having it available, considering they dish out less FPS... Things like DLSS, MFG, etc. should be a helping hand to the older gens, not a feature that you're forced to use even with the next gen '90 GPU because game devs can't be arsed to optimize games properly.
And yes, I know that in order to utilize such technologies, the GPUs require having certain cores available to process and handle all that AI/Fake Frame/Frame Gen tech, since it doesn't just get processed from thin air.... But still, this tech should be the crutch/helping hand of GPUs that need it, not the top of the line monstrosity.

I am glad they are working on bringing DLSS 4 features (not everything, but most of it) to previous gens, RTX 40 series owners of all kinds for example are getting fed well, despite the lack of MFG.

comments.text: Yes and no. More like devs are making several steps back in how they use said technology. The 5090 itself is not a bad card if you put aside its atrocious power demand. In fact it's the best rasterization card so far if you also dismiss its price. The fact that it has a very densely populated yet small PCB with a very good two slot cooler for this kind of performance is awesome. But at this rate, they will have to increase the PCB length yet again while maintaining that component density like adding 2 chipsets if not more smaller ones with a lot of VRAM around to keep a steady increase in raw performance. Which will also translate into "Your new PSU is a nuclear power plant".

comments.text:
People like to dunk on the 4000 and 5000 series but you gotta understand that we're very much at the end of Moore's Law. We simply cannot shrink the dies any more. No die shrinking, no big increases in raw performance. It's literally as simple as that. We're stuck with this amount of raw power for any number of generations until the next big tech breakthrough and god only knows when that's gonna happen.

For now all they can do is create and add more and more technologies on the cards to try and make things run better.
We're in a very weird transitory period. What we're seeing are the teething issues of these new techs. Hopefully it won't last much longer.

comments.text: @SWR112 It's not always code. It's also design. One simple example of that: Helldivers 2 last time I played it, was running meh on a 3070 Ti (okay, the card's VRAM is not great, but still). 1440p UW setup. The textures on the ground are low res everywhere. Many other textures and meshes are not that eye candy, smoke effects from bombs are quite smeared despite the scale of it looking impressive, but it's clearly not all that great (particle effects), nor the ambient lighting or ray tracing (by that I mean ray tracing in general, not just RTX and path tracing). The game struggles in native res and incites you to use the upscaling slider to obtain a more comfortable 100 fps, all while various entities and enemies spawn and despawn at rather short distances. I've seen better optimization even though HD2 is not the harshest game to run imo. There are worse examples ofc. Meanwhile there are games with higher res textures anything, decent effects and lighting running better natively because the devs are smart in how they use their tools at disposal.

comments.text:
@1ZosoLZ I mean, you can have your preference. Objectively speaking, however Black Ops 2 marks the last entry in which Activision allowed its studios true creative freedom. Then, Ghosts came out, which clearly didn't receive the support it needed. The game sjould've used an entirely new engine for Ghosts' scope, for features Infinity Ward either wanted themselves or promised during Ghosts' marketing campaign. And, yet, the dev team was, instead, forced into developing the game for two console generations, dividing their resources even further.  Worst still, they hired a writer ill-equipped for a videogame story. Especially one that, for one reason or another, still needed to emulate MW2's Michael-Bay-esque action. Sledgehammer's Vanguard writing division made the same mistake, but I digress.  And, of course, their was Extinction: A game mode I, to this day, look back on fondly but recognize its flaws. Mainly the fact that every match plays identically to the last. Now, a bit of procedural generation akin to L4D2's, would've made Extinction a repayable masterpiece. Unfortunately, just like with Ghosts' two most prominent modes, Extinction wasn't given the resources necessary to reach its full potential. 

The point is, whatever gripes you may or may not have with Black Ops 2, it had a clear direction. One which Treyarch was allowed to execute freely. Infinity Ward, in contrast, was dealt a bad hand and, IMO, played it poorly with their ambition. I empathize, don't get me wrong. I'm just realistic when it comes to their parent company, Activision. Their prioritizing of the bottom line will forever hold Call of Duty's talent back from greatness.

comments.text:
Funny how a lot of people in this comment section, don't seem to understand anything about computers. 

If you actually think you need an expensive card like this for gaming, you're clearly not building your pc properly. 
High end gpu's like this, are not needed for gaming and most certainly won't make your video game performance any better when most older gens cards will work just as good. You are completely wasting your money if you think you need an expensive card like this for gaming.

These cards are mainly geared towards a market of people that can afford to spend around 10-20k or more on a rig that is built for VFX artists, game developers that work with CPU and GPU based render engines including complex graphic designers that use these cards for high-resolution video editing. A 5090 card for gaming is overkill and not needed at all. For the current price that this card goes for, you can build yourself a decent rig for that amount of money that is more than capable of running the current gen games.
Most video games are CPU intensive and need a decent CPU and Ram for rendering the overall performance of the game. Your GPU is only going to make it look pretty. You can easily purchase an older series 8gb card for a great price and still run most, if not all of the current games on the market, depending on your hardware specs.. 

When knowing how to properly optimize everything on a low to mid range rig built for gaming, the overall performance of your game play and FPS, will still be great. You don't need to spend a stupid amount of money to achieve that goal...
